  "prompt": "What are proportional taxes?",
  "response": "Proportional taxes, also known as flat taxes, are a type of tax system where the tax rate remains constant regardless of the income level or amount being taxed. In this structure, individuals or entities pay the same percentage of their income or profits, meaning that everyone is taxed at the same rate.\n\nFor example, if a country has a proportional tax rate of 20%, both someone earning $30,000 and someone earning $300,000 would pay 20% of their respective incomes in taxes. This means the lower-income individual pays $6,000, while the higher-income individual pays $60,000.\n\nProponents of proportional taxes argue that they are simpler and more transparent than progressive tax systems (where the tax rate increases with income) and can encourage economic growth by not penalizing higher earnings. Critics, on the other hand, argue that proportional taxes can disproportionately affect lower-income individuals, as they may represent a larger percentage of their overall earnings compared to wealthier individuals.",
